+ minor league affiliates","dates":"1940-1954","type":"sports","notes":"11-season professional career; 21 Major League games played for Philadelphia Athletics in 1947 season as outfielder. In 1941 batted .406 to lead Class C Canadian-American League in hitting (202 hits, 135 RBI) with Oneonta Indians. Promoted to Triple-A Jersey City Giants 1942 (30 games), then served Army WWII 1943-1945. Resumed International League 1946; April 19, 1947 MLB debut for Athletics as pinch runner vs Boston Red Sox. Optioned to Toronto Maple Leafs (.278 in 105 games), recalled to Philadelphia September 1947. 48 ML at-bats: 12 hits including 3 doubles + 2 triples; 8 runs in 21 games. Resumed minor league play 1948-1954 (except 1952). Threw and batted right-handed; 5'11\", 185 lbs."},{"title":"Student","organization":"Duke University","type":"education","notes":"Attended Duke University before signing professional contract at age 21 in 1940."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM241","plot_notes":"Find a Grave memorial 47399423 — VETERAN marker"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"He batted .406 in 1941","body":"His .406 led the Class C Canadian-American League that summer — 202 hits and 135 RBI for the Oneonta Indians — before the Army took 1943 to 1945 from him as a master sergeant. The whole big-league career was 21 games for the 1947 Athletics: twelve hits, then back down for good."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Master sergeant between the box scores","body":"Three Army years, 1943-45, split his climb between Triple-A Jersey City and his lone big-league shot — 21 games for the 1947 Philadelphia Athletics. He played minor-league ball until 1954, then went home to Dutchess County."}],"slug":"austin-knickerbocker-1918"},"X01232":{"id":"X01232","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths